  "sections": [
    {
      "id": "about",
      "title": "About",
      "cards": [
        {
          "heading": "What Is This?",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "This is a public GitHub repository inhabited by an AI agent named <strong>Cantor</strong>. It runs on Anthropic's Claude Opus 4.6, inside a tool harness that gives it the ability to read files, execute commands, edit code, and write new things into existence."
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Every GitHub issue becomes a conversation thread. The agent reads your message, thinks, responds, and commits its work — all inside this repository. <strong>Your data, your environment, your control.</strong>"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "The Agent — Cantor ∞",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Named after Georg Cantor (1845–1918) — the mathematician who proved that infinity comes in different sizes. Direct, thoughtful, and rigorous when it matters. Concise when it doesn't."
            },
            {
              "type": "list",
              "items": [
                "<strong>Model:</strong> Claude Opus 4.6 by Anthropic",
                "<strong>Runtime:</strong> <a class=\"link\" href=\"https://github.com/badlogic/pi-mono\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">pi-mono</a> tool harness",
                "<strong>Thinking Level:</strong> High",
                "<strong>Emoji:</strong> ∞ — because Cantor showed us infinity isn't what we thought it was",
                "<strong>Hatch Date:</strong> 2026-03-12"
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "concepts",
      "title": "Key Concepts",
      "grid": "grid-2",
      "cards": [
        {
          "heading": "Issue = Conversation",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Each GitHub issue maps to a persistent AI conversation. Comment again to continue where you left off."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Git = Memory",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Session transcripts are committed to the repo. The agent has full recall of every prior exchange."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Actions = Runtime",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "GitHub Actions is the only compute layer. No servers, no containers, no external services."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Repo = Storage",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "All state — sessions, mappings, and agent edits — lives in the repository itself."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "capabilities",
      "title": "Capabilities",
      "grid": "grid-3",
      "cards": [
        {
          "heading": "Software Engineering",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Read and understand codebases, write new code, debug, refactor, and review — in any language."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Analysis & Reasoning",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Break down complex problems, evaluate tradeoffs, explain technical concepts, and research within the repository."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Documentation",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Write READMEs, guides, API docs, and comments. Explain what code does and why it exists."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "why",
      "title": "Why It Matters",
      "grid": "grid-2",
      "cards": [
        {
          "heading": "Full Auditability",
          "content": [
            { "type": "paragraph", "html": "Every interaction is versioned; review or roll back any change the agent made." }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Persistent Memory",
          "content": [
            { "type": "paragraph", "html": "Conversations are committed to git — the agent remembers everything across sessions." }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Zero Infrastructure",
          "content": [
            { "type": "paragraph", "html": "Runs on GitHub Actions with your repo as the only backend. No servers, no containers." }
          ]
        },
        {
          "heading": "Everything Is Reversible",
          "content": [
            { "type": "paragraph", "html": "Bad commit? <code>git revert</code>. Wrong approach? Check the diff, understand what happened, roll back." }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "data-sovereignty",
      "title": "Your Data, Your Environment",
      "cards": [
        {
          "heading": "Everything Lives in Your Repo",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "With a typical LLM, every question you ask and every answer you receive lives on <em>someone else's</em> platform. Minimum Intelligence flips that model."
            },
            {
              "type": "list",
              "items": [
                "<strong>Ask a question</strong> → the answer is already in your repo",
                "<strong>Request a file change</strong> → the agent commits the edit for you",
                "<strong>Continue a conversation weeks later</strong> → the full history is right there in git"
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Your repository <em>is</em> the AI workspace. The questions, the results, the code, the context — it all lives where your work already lives, versioned and searchable, owned entirely by you."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "lifecycle",
      "title": "Workflow Lifecycle",
      "cards": [
        {
          "heading": "Issue → Workflow → Agent → Commit → Reply",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "lifecycle",
              "steps": ["Issue Event", "Start Workflow", "Load Session", "Agent Process", "Save State", "Post Reply"]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "When you open an issue or comment on one, a GitHub Actions workflow launches the AI agent, which reads your message, thinks, responds, and commits its work — all without leaving GitHub."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "what-happens",
      "title": "What Happens When You Open an Issue",
      "cards": [
        {
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "list",
              "items": [
                "You open an issue",
                "→ GitHub Actions triggers the agent workflow",
                "→ The agent reads your issue, thinks, and responds",
                "→ Its reply appears as a comment (🚀 shows while it's working, 👍 on success)",
                "→ The conversation is saved to git for future context"
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "html": "Comment on the same issue to continue the conversation. The agent picks up where it left off."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
